post_text: Teacher Tuesday!
shared_text:
Cline Ponies
September 8 at 3:53 PM ¬∑

Happy Text Tuesday! Today we are featuring two of our amazing third grade teachers, Ms. Calligan and Mrs. James! This is Ms. Calligan's third year teaching and her first year teaching at Cline. Her favorite poem is "Invitation" by Shel Silverstein. Mrs. James has been teaching at Cline for many years. One of her favorite quotes is by Michel Legend..."The more I live, the more I learn. The more I learn, the more I realize, the less I know". Thank you Ms. Calligan and Mrs. James for growing a love for reading within our students at Cline. #readersareleaders

text: Tonight the Board approved an amended calendar with an adjusted bell schedule adding 5 min. As we face the unknowns of COVID, it is possible that shutdowns would be necessary. By increasing min, we would build in enough to cover 3 missed days, meet state req min w/o adding days.

post_text: Tonight the Board approved an amended calendar with an adjusted bell schedule increasing the school day by 5 minutes. As we face the unknowns of COVID in the 2020 - 2021 school year, it is possible that shutdowns would be necessary at individual campuses or across the District. By increasing the minutes each school day, we would build in enough additional minutes to have enough to cover a total of 3 missed school days and still meet the state requirement of 75,600 minutes without needing additional make-up days.
text: Tonight the Board approved an amended calendar with an adjusted bell schedule increasing the school day by 5 minutes. As we face the unknowns of COVID in the 2020 - 2021 school year, it is possible that shutdowns would be necessary at individual campuses or across the District. By increasing the minutes each school day, we would build in enough additional minutes to have enough to cover a total of 3 missed school days and still meet the state requirement of 75,600 minutes without needing additional make-up days.

post_text:
FISD Care-opoly
For some of our neighbors in Friendswood ISD, navigating the challenges of Covid-19 have been like being pieces in a real game of Monopoly. Families have been dealt unimaginable "Chance" cards that have left them struggling to stay on the board. They need help right now and we're looking to connect those who are in a position to help with those with greatest need. This is our first round of FISD Care-opoly, and we hope that you will go to your church small groups, close network of friends, or even your neighborhood to come together to adopt one of our FISD Care-opoly Families. Please email info@fisdcares.com or visit www.fisdcares.com for more information!

post_text:
Fellow Mustangs:

It wasn‚Äôt long ago we all stood together as a community elbow to elbow as we rebuilt Friendswood. Our true ‚Äúmustang colors‚Äù shone brightly for the world to see. We were FRIENDSWOOD STRONG.

Now, we are faced with COVID-19. We are told to separate - to practice social distancing. So we must come together to show our strength in a different way. As a community, let‚Äôs show our spirit by creating and POSTING a mustang in the windows of our homes and businesses. Art teachers will be sharing videos today to help guide you. These are meant to be a reminder of our community togetherness so that when you are out taking a walk or going for a drive you will see these mustangs and know that we are forever connected! When you‚Äôre done, be sure to leave a comment below with a picture!

Mustang Pride! #OutOfTheBlue

post_text:
What better way to start the week than with a sweet story? First-grader Jessica Woitena and her PAL senior Haley Permenter have met every week for the past year. Each week, the friends talk, play games and take a picture together. Despite not being able to meet face-to-face the past two weeks, the pair has continued their meetings. Haley has FaceTimed Jessica to talk and see what she has been working on, and they have still managed to get their weekly picture together. On Saturday, Haley surprised Jessica by dropping off a treat for her to decorate and eat, and asked her to FaceTime her once she was done decorating the cookie so she could see it.

Simple acts of kindness like this go a long way and remind us all that no matter what is going on in the world, love knows no distance. üíô #OutOfTheBlue

FISD is continuing to closely monitor information concerning coronavirus (COVID-19) and follow the guidance and expertise of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), Galveston County Health Department and Texas Department of State Health Services.

FISD has a scheduled conference call Friday afternoon with the greater Houston area school districts and State Health Services as well as meeting with Harris County Health officials to discuss strategic planning for the return of staff and students after Spring Break. We will update our staff and parents of FISD's plan for a safe transition after this call.

post_text:
It is with great sadness that we share the loss of FHS senior Joshua Taylor Betthauser.

A visitation will be held on Thursday, January 9, from 5- 7 pm at Forest Park East Funeral Home. A Celebration of Life will be held on Friday, January 10th at 10 am at Hope Lutheran Church in Friendswood.

Friendswood High School has staff trained to help with the needs of students, parents and school personnel at difficult times such as this. We have counselors available for any student who may need or want help or any type of assistance surrounding a loss. The Friendswood ISD Social and Emotional Learning page has resources for handling grief at http://myfisd.com/sel/sel-resources/. School counselors can also provide additional resources for outside counseling.

Joshua's mother Mary Ann Betthauser is an employee of Friendswood ISD. Please keep this family in your prayers.
